In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** in `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity => HandleBackground())
            .OnStop(activity => HandleBackground()));
#elif IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(app => HandleBackground()));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}

static void HandleBackground()
{
    // Your background logic here
}
```

**Key points:**
- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to target each platform
- **Android**: `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnStart`, `OnDestroy`, etc.
- **iOS**: `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.
- Each callback receives the platform-native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS)
